    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hi, i'm in the middle of buying my first house in austin and i'm a bit confused. my realtor mentioned my earnest money is being held in an escrow account. can u explain what that actually means and why they don't just give it to the seller right away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Earnest money is a deposit you place with a neutral third party, the escrow company, to show the seller you are serious about buying the house. It acts like a good-faith deposit, and the escrow account keeps it safe until the sale officially closes. The funds aren't immediately given to the seller because they are held as security until all contract conditions are met, like inspections and financing approval. If you back out without a valid reason, the seller might keep it, but if the sale closes, it's typically applied toward your down payment.",
